      "content": [
        {
          "text": "Get the result: The calculator will process the data based on the selected calculation and display the result. For example, if you input the data set {1, 3, 5, 7, 9} and select the mean calculation, the calculator will output \\(5\\).",
          "annotations": {
            "bold": false,
            "italic": false,
            "strikethrough": false,
            "underline": false,
            "code": false,
            "color": "default"
          }
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "151e4db6-1239-803c-a309-e50696bdddaf",
      "type": "heading_2",
      "content": [
        {
          "text": "5. Formula Origin",
          "annotations": {
            "bold": false,
            "italic": false,
            "strikethrough": false,
            "underline": false,
            "code": false,
            "color": "default"
          }
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "151e4db6-1239-8008-bc78-d78ce2aff418",
      "type": "paragraph",
      "content": [
        {
          "text": "The concepts and formulas in statistics have evolved over centuries. The idea of measures of central tendency like the mean has been used since ancient times in simple forms of accounting and record-keeping. The formal development of statistical theory began in the 17th and 18th centuries with the works of mathematicians and scientists interested in understanding probability and the analysis of data. For example, the variance and standard deviation formulas were developed as ways to quantify the spread of data, which became crucial in fields like astronomy (to account for errors in measurements) and later in social sciences and economics as the need to analyze large amounts of data and understand variability grew. The covariance formula was developed to study the relationships between variables, which is essential in regression analysis and understanding the interdependence of different factors in various fields of study.",
          "annotations": {
            "bold": false,
            "italic": false,
            "strikethrough": false,
            "underline": false,
            "code": false,
            "color": "default"
          }
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "151e4db6-1239-80e9-98a8-e4f402a01024",
      "type": "heading_2",
      "content": [
        {
          "text": "6. FAQ",
          "annotations": {
            "bold": false,
            "italic": false,
            "strikethrough": false,
            "underline": false,
            "code": false,
            "color": "default"
          }
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "151e4db6-1239-80a5-93c0-ca187889f016",
      "type": "heading_3",
      "content": [
        {
          "text": "Q1: Can a data set have more than one mode?",
          "annotations": {
            "bold": false,
            "italic": false,
            "strikethrough": false,
            "underline": false,
            "code": false,
            "color": "default"
          }
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "151e4db6-1239-80c2-9689-db31b7e497dd",
      "type": "paragraph",
      "content": [
        {
          "text": "A: Yes, a data set can have more than one mode if multiple values occur with the same highest frequency. For example, in the set {2, 3, 3, 5, 5, 7}, both \\(3\\) and \\(5\\) are modes.",
          "annotations": {
            "bold": false,
            "italic": false,
            "strikethrough": false,
            "underline": false,
            "code": false,
            "color": "default"
          }
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "151e4db6-1239-80da-8d66-d8e3d5e3ff8d",
      "type": "heading_3",
      "content": [
        {
          "text": "Q2: What if the data set has an even number of values and the two middle values for the median are different?",
          "annotations": {
            "bold": false,
            "italic": false,
            "strikethrough": false,
            "underline": false,
            "code": false,
            "color": "default"
          }
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "151e4db6-1239-8072-b803-f5d6171b4963",
      "type": "paragraph",
      "content": [
        {
          "text": "A: You take the average of those two middle values. For example, in the set {2, 4, 6, 8}, the median is \\(\\frac{4+6}{2}=5\\)",
          "annotations": {
            "bold": false,
            "italic": false,
            "strikethrough": false,
            "underline": false,
            "code": false,
            "color": "default"
          }
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "151e4db6-1239-801e-8bd9-f79e8aa078c7",
      "type": "heading_3",
      "content": [
        {
          "text": "Q3: Why is the denominator \\(n- 1\\) in the sample variance formula?",
          "annotations": {
            "bold": false,
            "italic": false,
            "strikethrough": false,
            "underline": false,
            "code": false,
            "color": "default"
          }
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "151e4db6-1239-80d5-8c52-e3a6d066d4f4",
      "type": "paragraph",
      "content": [
        {
          "text": "A: Using \\(n - 1\\) instead of \\(n\\) gives a better estimate of the population variance from a sample. It corrects for the fact that the sample mean is used instead of the population mean and provides an unbiased estimate.",
          "annotations": {
            "bold": false,
            "italic": false,
            "strikethrough": false,
            "underline": false,
            "code": false,
            "color": "default"
          }
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "151e4db6-1239-80b6-84e2-f0535640ac2f",
      "type": "heading_3",
      "content": [
        {
          "text": "Q4: How does the standard deviation help in understanding data?",
          "annotations": {
            "bold": false,
            "italic": false,
            "strikethrough": false,
            "underline": false,
            "code": false,
            "color": "default"
          }
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "151e4db6-1239-80a7-892f-d2d8776a1121",
      "type": "paragraph",
      "content": [
        {
          "text": "A: The standard deviation gives an idea of how much the data points typically deviate from the mean. A small standard deviation indicates that the data points are close to the mean, while a large standard deviation means the data is more spread out.",
          "annotations": {
            "bold": false,
            "italic": false,
            "strikethrough": false,
            "underline": false,
            "code": false,
            "color": "default"
          }
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "151e4db6-1239-80a1-afb4-fdf5e2b7bb4a",
      "type": "heading_3",
      "content": [
        {
          "text": "Q5: Can the covariance be negative?",
          "annotations": {
            "bold": false,
            "italic": false,
            "strikethrough": false,
            "underline": false,
            "code": false,
            "color": "default"
          }
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "151e4db6-1239-80ac-b38b-eb8089fd0742",
      "type": "paragraph",
      "content": [
        {
          "text": "A: Yes, the covariance can be negative. A negative covariance indicates an inverse relationship between the two variables, meaning that as one variable increases, the other tends to decrease.",
          "annotations": {
            "bold": false,
            "italic": false,
            "strikethrough": false,
            "underline": false,
            "code": false,
            "color": "default"
          }
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "151e4db6-1239-8002-b5dc-d2e30b4f4d65",
      "type": "heading_2",
      "content": [
        {
          "text": "7. Solved Examples on Statistics Calculator",
          "annotations": {
